<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="499" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,957,1128]" pageId="12" pageNumber="499">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1030,1056]" pageId="12" pageNumber="499">Remarks.</emphasis>
The specimen studied agrees with the description. It is the first time that this species is recorded in 
<collectingRegion box="[151,278,1066,1092]" country="Brazil" name="Goias" pageId="12" pageNumber="499">Goiás state</collectingRegion>
. As already highlighted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Duarte, T. &amp; Lecci, L. S." box="[579,834,1066,1092]" pageId="12" pageNumber="499" pagination="291 - 300" refId="ref8607" refString="Duarte, T. &amp; Lecci, L. S. (2016) New species and records of Anacroneuria (Plecoptera: Perlidae) from the northeastern semi-arid region of Brazil. Zootaxa, 4079 (2), 291 - 300. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4079.2.10" type="journal article" year="2016">Duarte &amp; Lecci (2016)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duarte &amp; Lecci" authorityYear="2016" box="[845,956,1066,1092]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Anacroneuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="499" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singela">
<emphasis box="[845,956,1066,1092]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="499">A. singela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zwick, 1972:" authorityYear="1155" box="[1098,1203,1066,1092]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Anacroneuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="499" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="debilis">
<emphasis box="[1098,1203,1066,1092]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="499">A. debilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; however, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duarte &amp; Lecci" authorityYear="2016" box="[1325,1436,1066,1092]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Anacroneuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="499" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singela">
<emphasis box="[1325,1436,1066,1092]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="499">A. singela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a more robust penial armature, especially in the keel and terminal tube.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
